# Phase 1 Checklist — Foundation (Project Setup + Auth)

Goal: a deployed, empty CRM with the full database schema in place, that you can securely log into with a seeded user.

## 1. Monorepo Setup
- [ ] Initialize git repo, set up workspaces (pnpm/npm/yarn) with `apps/web`, `apps/api`, `packages/shared`
- [ ] `apps/web`: Next.js app (TypeScript)
- [ ] `apps/api`: Express app (TypeScript)
- [ ] `packages/shared`: shared TS types (e.g. re-exported Prisma types, shared DTOs)
- [ ] Shared/base tsconfig, eslint, prettier config across apps
- [ ] Root-level dev script to run both apps concurrently
- [ ] `.gitignore` and `.env.example` for each app

## 2. Database & Prisma Schema
- [ ] Provision Postgres (Render instance, and/or local Postgres for dev)
- [ ] Initialize Prisma in `apps/api`
- [ ] Write `schema.prisma` with all 6 models: User, Company, Contact, Deal, Task, Note
  - [ ] Enums: `Role` (owner/admin/member), `DealStage` (Lead/Contacted/Proposal/Negotiation/Won/Lost), `TaskStatus` (todo/done)
  - [ ] Relations: Company → Contacts, Company → Deals, Contact → Deal (primary_contact), Contact/Deal → Tasks, Contact/Deal → Notes
- [ ] Run initial migration (`prisma migrate dev`)
- [ ] Sanity-check schema via Prisma Studio or a test query

## 3. Seed Script (replaces public registration)
- [ ] Create `prisma/seed.ts`
- [ ] Script creates initial user(s): name, email, bcrypt-hashed password, role = `owner`
- [ ] Wire up `"prisma": { "seed": "..." }` in `package.json`
- [ ] Run seed locally and confirm user exists in DB

## 4. Express API — Core Setup
- [ ] Express entrypoint with TypeScript
- [ ] Middleware: `cors` (specific origin + `credentials: true`), `cookie-parser`, JSON body parser
- [ ] Centralized error-handling middleware
- [ ] `GET /health` route
- [ ] Prisma client singleton module

## 5. Auth Implementation
- [ ] bcrypt password verification helper
- [ ] JWT sign/verify helpers (`JWT_SECRET` from env)
- [ ] `POST /auth/login` — verify credentials, sign JWT, set httpOnly cookie
- [ ] `POST /auth/logout` — clear cookie
- [ ] `GET /auth/me` — verify JWT from cookie, return current user
- [ ] Auth middleware — attaches `req.user`, returns 401 if missing/invalid
- [ ] Test middleware on a temporary protected route

## 6. Next.js Frontend
- [ ] API client wrapper (`fetch` with `credentials: 'include'`, base URL from env)
- [ ] Login page (email/password form → `/auth/login`)
- [ ] Auth context/provider — calls `/auth/me` on load, exposes `user` + loading state
- [ ] Protected route handling — redirect to `/login` if unauthenticated
- [ ] Placeholder dashboard page (protected) showing logged-in user's name
- [ ] Logout action

## 7. Environment & Config
- [ ] `apps/api` env vars: `DATABASE_URL`, `JWT_SECRET`, `CORS_ORIGIN`, `PORT`
- [ ] `apps/web` env vars: `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL`
- [ ] Document required env vars in README

## 8. Deploy to Render
- [ ] Create Postgres instance on Render
- [ ] Create web service for `apps/api` (build/start commands, env vars)
- [ ] Create web service for `apps/web` (build/start commands, env vars)
- [ ] Run migration + seed against production DB
- [ ] Production cookie config: `secure: true`, `sameSite: 'none'`
- [ ] End-to-end test in production (see Definition of Done below)

## 9. Definition of Done
- [ ] Can log in with seeded user via the deployed Next.js app
- [ ] Refreshing the page keeps the session alive
- [ ] Logout clears the session and redirects to login
- [ ] Visiting the dashboard while logged out redirects to login
- [ ] Full schema (all 6 models) exists in production DB, ready for Phase 2

